            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Jordan Jones\u2019s story is one steeped in the layered sounds of the Bay Area. Raised in West Oakland, he was the only child of a longshoreman father and a second-grade teacher mother. His childhood soundscape was a mix of his mother\u2019s patient lessons, the distant horn of container ships from the port, and the crackle of the old AM/FM radio in his father's garage. It was there, tinkering with the dial, that Jordan first fell in love with the power of a disembodied voice to tell a compelling story.\n\nHe enrolled in Media Studies at San Francisco State University, fascinated by how narratives were constructed. However, the theoretical nature of his classes felt disconnected from the hands-on craft he craved. A pivotal internship at a small, independent podcast company in the Mission District changed everything. He discovered a natural talent for audio editing, finding the rhythm in a conversation and shaping it into a seamless narrative. When offered a full-time assistant producer role, Jordan made the difficult decision to leave college, trusting his practical skills over a diploma.\n\nNow 31, Jordan is a respected producer for a major tech information platform. His daily 8.1-mile commute from his Inner Richmond apartment is a ritual. Aboard the Muni bus, headphones on, he isn\u2019t listening to music but deconstructing other podcasts\u2014analyzing pacing, sound design, and interview techniques. His $95,000 salary affords him a comfortable, if not lavish, life in a city he both loves and resents for its ever-rising costs. He enjoys the quiet, foggy streets of his neighborhood and its proximity to Golden Gate Park, a welcome escape from the downtown hustle.\n\nHis social life is a bridge between two worlds: old friends from Oakland who keep him grounded and newer work colleagues who talk of IPOs and funding rounds. While he excels at amplifying others' voices, his deepest aspiration is to launch his own podcast\u2014a series documenting the gentrification and cultural shifts of the Bay Area, told through the stories of people like his parents. Jordan\u2019s dream is to one day own the narrative, not just produce it, giving a voice back to the communities that first taught him how to listen."
