            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was ten, cross-legged on the cool, dusty concrete of his father\u2019s garage. While his dad cleaned grease from his knuckles, Jordan twisted the big, silver dial on the AM radio. He tuned past static and music until a clear voice emerged, telling a story about a town he\u2019d never seen. He felt a profound, electric connection, a sudden understanding that a voice alone could build a world. That day, sound became more than noise; it became a destination. This planted the seed of his life's obsession with narrative audio.\n\n2.\nThe job offer from the Mission podcast company felt like a lifeline in an ocean of academic theory. He was 20. He remembers holding his phone, the producer\u2019s voice a stark contrast to the dense media theory textbook open on his desk. Telling his mother, a teacher who revered education, that he was leaving SF State was the hardest conversation of his life. It was a terrifying leap, but the first decision that felt entirely his own, choosing the tangible craft of storytelling over a piece of paper.\n\n3.\nOn the 38-Geary Muni bus last winter, surrounded by the damp quiet of a foggy morning, he was deconstructing a new true-crime podcast. He wasn\u2019t listening to the story; he was isolating the musical sting, noting the clumsy edit on a guest\u2019s breath, critiquing the host\u2019s pacing. A sudden, faint pang of loss hit him. He realized his passion had become a science. This mastery was his livelihood, but it had cost him the simple magic of just being a listener.\n\n4.\nAt a friend's birthday party in a sleek Hayes Valley bar a few months ago, he felt like a ghost drifting between conversations. To his left, his friends from Oakland laughed about shared memories and worried about another neighborhood spot closing. To his right, his tech colleagues debated the valuation of a new app. In that moment, Jordan felt the chasm, the two separate narratives of one Bay Area. It filled him with a quiet urgency to build a bridge between them with his work.\n\n5.\nHe was visiting his parents in West Oakland last month when his dad mentioned an old friend, a fellow longshoreman, had been priced out and moved to Tracy. Just then, the low, mournful horn of a container ship sounded from the port. The sound, once a comfort, now felt like a eulogy. His dream solidified in that instant. His podcast wouldn't just be a project; it was a debt he owed to the voices and sounds that raised him, a way to document the history being erased."
